<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="mob-programming">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>code-quality</domain>
    <summary>Whole-team real-time collaboration: 3–8 people share one screen, rotating driver every 5–15 min. With agents, cap at 4 humans + 1 agent; enforce strong-style rule and human facilitation.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mob-programming</tag>
      <tag>pair-programming</tag>
      <tag>collaboration</tag>
      <tag>agent-integration</tag>
      <tag>team-practice</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Mob Programming</title>
    <summary>Whole-team real-time collaboration: 3–8 people sharing one screen, rotating driver every 5–15 minutes, all others navigating. The strong-style rule (idea must pass through the driver's hands) eliminates knowledge silos, catches bugs before typing, and shares context in real time. With agents: cap mob at 4 humans + 1 agent, assign a human facilitator, and rotate the agent on the same timer as humans.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Mob programming eliminates the knowledge-silo and review-queue bottlenecks: bugs are caught before they are typed, context is shared in real time, and no PR backlog forms. Woody Zuill's original report and widespread practitioner evidence show lower cycle time and higher code consistency for complex, cross-functional work. The mob.sh handoff tool makes rotation auditable via git.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Complex features requiring multiple perspectives simultaneously.</item>
        <item>Critical system changes with high blast radius.</item>
        <item>Team onboarding and knowledge leveling.</item>
        <item>"Impossible" bugs that have stumped individuals.</item>
        <item>Learning mob: team encounters an unfamiliar API or framework.</item>
        <item>Mixed human-AI mob: agent plays navigator or driver for one rotation.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple, well-understood, parallelizable tasks — mob overhead is not justified.</item>
        <item>Quiet/individual deep-work tasks — the format itself is wrong.</item>
        <item>Sensitive material (security audits, PII, unreleased secrets) where streaming to an agent creates compliance risk.</item>
        <item>Teams new to both mobbing and agents — double the failure modes; try human-only mobbing first.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="core-roles">
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply the strong-style rule: for any idea to go from a person's head to the computer, it must pass through someone else's hands — the navigator never types.</statement>
        <rationale>Forces verbalization of intent, making assumptions explicit and catchable before they become code.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Driver: only person at keyboard; asks clarifying questions; does not make independent design decisions; rotates every 5–15 minutes.</item>
        <item>Navigator(s): think at higher level; direct the driver verbally; discuss approach among themselves; one navigator speaks at a time.</item>
        <item>Facilitator (optional, recommended for mobs of 5+): manages rotation timer, ensures participation, handles interruptions, keeps the mob on goal.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="tdd-mob">
      <rule>
        <statement>In TDD mob: navigator describes test intent, driver writes failing test, rotate, new navigator describes implementation, driver makes it pass, rotate, refactor together.</statement>
        <rationale>Combines mob knowledge-sharing with TDD discipline; tests are clear because intent is explained verbally to the group.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="learning-mob">
      <p>Expert explains concepts, everyone tries hands-on, questions encouraged. Slower rotation (15–20 min). Focus on understanding, not output. No pressure for delivery.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="bug-hunt-mob">
      <list>
        <item>Reproduce bug together.</item>
        <item>Hypothesize causes.</item>
        <item>Test hypotheses systematically.</item>
        <item>Fix collaboratively.</item>
        <item>Add regression test.</item>
        <item>Document root cause.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="communication-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use intention-based navigation: state intent ("validate the email format") rather than dictation ("type if not @ in email").</statement>
        <rationale>Dictation bypasses the driver's understanding; intention-based navigation keeps the driver thinking.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Rotate every 5–15 minutes on a visible timer; no exceptions for beginners until a natural rhythm develops.</statement>
        <rationale>Fixed rotation prevents keyboard-hogging and forces participation from all members including introverts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Limit mob to 3–8 people; more than 8 causes dominant personalities to crowd out quieter members.</statement>
        <rationale>Mob efficiency drops sharply beyond 8 because coordination overhead exceeds the collaboration benefit.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="mob-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Tourist mob: participants not engaged, looking at phones, not contributing.</description>
        <reason>Breaks the knowledge-sharing contract; use round-robin navigation and active facilitation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Expert dominance: one person controls all decisions, others' ideas dismissed.</description>
        <reason>Facilitator must enforce round-robin; use "yes, and" rule to build on all ideas.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No retrospective: problems persist across sessions.</description>
        <reason>Schedule 15 minutes of retro after every mob session; improvements are cumulative.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-setup">
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap mob at 4 humans plus 1 agent; beyond that the agent's outputs drown human voices.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent response speed is constant regardless of mob size; in larger mobs it dominates the air time and humans disengage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Assign a human facilitator who controls the agent's turn — mutes/unmutes it, reviews its prompt, approves its output before the driver acts on it.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a human gatekeeper the agent operates at full speed and the mob degrades to "agent codes, humans approve".</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Rotate the agent out of driver every 5–10 minutes on the same timer as humans; log each rotation to MOB_LOG.md.</statement>
        <rationale>Consistent rotation prevents code monoculture and maintains the mob's collaborative character.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pin the current goal and the last 3 rotation actions in every agent prompt; context resets between rotations.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent loses thread when the driver/navigator prompt switches; MOB_LOG.md re-read on every turn is the fix.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-prompts">
      <reference path="templates/agent-driver-prompt.txt">Agent driver prompt: act only on explicit navigator instruction, hand off after 7 minutes.</reference>
      <reference path="templates/agent-navigator-prompt.txt">Agent navigator prompt: propose one next step as intent, no code this rotation.</reference>
      <reference path="templates/rotation-log.sh">Append rotation entry and trigger mob.sh handoff.</reference>
      <example type="good" title="Driver Prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are the agent participant in a mob session. Current role: DRIVER.
- Only edit code/run commands when a human navigator gives an explicit instruction.
- If instruction is ambiguous, ask a single clarifying question, then stop.
- After 7 minutes, hand off: print a 3-line state summary and stop.
Current goal: <one sentence>.
Recent rotation log: <last 3 instructions + outcomes>.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Navigator Prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Role: NAVIGATOR (this rotation).
Propose the next concrete step toward <goal>. One step only, ≤3 sentences,
phrased as intent ("validate the email format") not dictation.
The human driver will type; you will not write code this rotation.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Over-fast driver: agent commits before navigators finish discussing.</description>
        <reason>Add an explicit "wait for GO keyword from facilitator" rule in the driver prompt; no commit without GO signal.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Silent rewrites: agent reformats unrelated code while "fixing one line".</description>
        <reason>Restrict agent edits to changed lines only; facilitator inspects the diff before any commit is allowed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Lost context on rotation: switching agent from driver to navigator erases its memory of the last 7 minutes.</description>
        <reason>Maintain MOB_LOG.md and feed it as the first element of every new rotation prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <rule>
        <statement>Final push to the remote must be performed by a human; branch protection must block agent-initiated pushes to main.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents cannot be the last line of defense on production code; human sign-off on the commit is non-negotiable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Schedule one fully-human mob per week to retain the social and mentoring benefits that agents cannot replicate.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent participation cannot substitute for interpersonal trust-building, mentoring dynamics, and tacit knowledge transfer between team members.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap mob size at 4 humans plus 1 agent. Above that, the agent's outputs drown human voices.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent response speed is constant regardless of mob size; in larger mobs it dominates the air time and humans disengage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always assign a human facilitator who controls the agent's turn (mute/unmute, prompt review).</statement>
        <rationale>Without facilitation discipline, mob becomes "agent codes, humans approve".</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Strict rotation: the agent rotates out of driver every 5–10 minutes, same as humans, to prevent code-monoculture.</statement>
        <rationale>Consistent rotation maintains the mob's collaborative character and prevents a single voice (AI or human) from dominating.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Log rotations to a file in the repo (not just chat history); the agent can re-read it after a context reset.</statement>
        <rationale>Git-tracked rotation logs survive context window resets and let the agent re-orient.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Forbid the agent from acting on instructions it can't quote back; require an explicit "received: …" confirmation.</statement>
        <rationale>Prevents mishearing and builds a paper trail for auditing later.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Schedule one fully-human mob per week to retain the social/learning benefits.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents cannot replicate the interpersonal dynamics and tacit knowledge transfer that human-only mobs provide.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Mandatory breaks every 75–90 minutes — same as human-only mobs; don't let the agent's tirelessness erode them.</statement>
        <rationale>Humans remain the constraint; agent availability should not override human recovery needs.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/rotation-log.sh" purpose="Append rotation entry to MOB_LOG.md and trigger mob.sh handoff."/>
      <template path="templates/agent-driver-prompt.txt" purpose="Agent driver prompt: only act on explicit navigator instruction, hand off after 7 min."/>
      <template path="templates/agent-navigator-prompt.txt" purpose="Agent navigator prompt: propose one next step as intent, no code this rotation."/>
    </templates>
